# Retailer Routing Guide Framework

## Overview

Retailers and distributors often provide routing guides that define how shipments must be prepared, scheduled, labeled, and delivered. These guides ensure consistency in shipping processes and help retailers manage inbound logistics efficiently.

Wholesale operations teams must follow routing guides carefully to avoid shipment delays, delivery refusals, or financial penalties.

---

## Purpose of Routing Guides

Routing guides exist to:

• standardize shipment preparation  
• ensure retailer warehouse efficiency  
• control carrier selection  
• maintain delivery scheduling discipline  
• reduce inbound processing delays  

Compliance with routing guides protects operational reliability and retailer relationships.

---

## Common Routing Guide Requirements

Retail routing guides typically define requirements for:

### Carrier Selection
Retailers may specify approved carriers or transportation methods.

Examples include:

• designated freight carriers  
• small parcel carrier requirements  
• consolidation programs  

### Shipment Scheduling

Retailers often require shipments to be scheduled through appointment systems.

Examples include:

• delivery appointment portals  
• warehouse receiving schedules  
• delivery time windows  

### Packaging and Labeling

Retailers may require standardized labeling formats.

Examples include:

• carton labeling standards  
• pallet labeling requirements  
• SSCC labels  
• barcode placement

### Documentation

Retailers may require specific documentation such as:

• advance ship notices (ASN)  
• packing lists  
• bill of lading documentation  

---

## Operational Responsibility

Routing guide compliance is typically managed by:

• logistics teams  
• warehouse operations  
• order management teams  

Operations teams must verify routing instructions before shipments leave the warehouse.

---

## Consequences of Non-Compliance

Failure to follow routing guides can result in:

• retailer chargebacks  
• rejected shipments  
• delayed receiving  
• damaged retailer relationships  

Strong operational controls help prevent these issues.

---

## Final Note

Routing guides are a critical part of wholesale logistics operations. When teams follow these requirements consistently, shipments move smoothly through retailer receiving processes and operational performance remains stable.
